column123: Higher rebate levels (as indicated in Rebate 2) for rural Alaskans to compensate for shipping costs
An additional $50 rebate granted to those who provided proof of recycled replaced refrigerators
Offered rebates as percentage of appliance price rather than at a flat level - changed to flat level in Phase 2. Additional rebate of $75 with proof of recycling in Phase 1.
Offered rebates as percentage of appliance price for boilers, clothes washers, dishwashers, freezers, refrigerators and water heaters
Offered rebate for solar water heaters as 25% of purchase price or $2500, whichever is lower
In Phase 2, rebates for Furnaces (Propane) dropped to $300
An additional $50 rebate granted to those who provided proof of recycled replaced freezers and $100 to recycled replaced refrigerators
A limited Phase 2 was offered to survivors of the Joplin tornado which offered $250 rebates for Energy Star clothes washer and refrigerator purchases
Phase 2 ($93,603 of $928,000 total disbursements) of the program was means-tested

Phase 1 ($7.8 million of $8.8 million total disbursements) were percentage-based instant rebates for clothes washers, dishwashers, freezers and refrigerators) - rebates listed under "Rebate 2" represent flat rebate amounts offered in Phase 2
An additional $100 rebate for boiler reset controls was offered as they were required for new boiler installations in New Hampshire
An additional $50 rebate granted to those who provided proof of recycled replaced refrigerators

To redeem "Rebate 2" levels, consumers had to purchase high efficiency "bundles" (clothes washer, dishwasher and refrigerator all at once); additional rebates granted for proof of recycled replaced appliances- ($25 for clothes washers, $25 for freezers, $30 for refrigerators and $55 for the bundle

Phase 2 ($1.3 million of $11.02 million in total disbursements) of the program was means-tested - a full 100% rebate was offered for all boilers, all  furnaces and heat pumps (air-source) with proof of recycling; non-means tested flat level rebates for clothes washers, dishwashers, refrigerators, and water heaters made up Phase 1
Rebate levels were increased on August 2, 2010 after only about $2 million of $11.994 million appropration was disbursed by that point - post-August 2 rebate levels reflected here

Phase 2 rebate levels (~$8 million of the $23 million appropriated) were decreased following the logjam to reserve higher rebates in Phase 1 - Phase 1 rebates are reflected here; an additional $75 rebate was offered for recycling any replaced appliance
Phase 2 rebate levels decreased for Energy Star refrigerators from $75 to $50
